ackdrop, placing it in the context of globalization, digitization, and new media. Drawing connections with the other arts, in particular visual art and architecture, he expands the definition of Western art music to include forms of composition, experimental music, sound art, and crossover work from across the spectrum, inside and beyond the concert hall. Each chapter is a critical consideration of a wide range of composers, performers, works, and institutions, and develops a broad and rich picture of the new music ecosystem, from North American string quartets to Lebanese improvisers, from electroacoustic music studios in South America to ruined pianos in the Australian outback. Rutherford-Johnson puts forth a new approach to the study of contemporary music that relies less on taxonomies of style and technique than on the comparison of different responses to common themes of permission, fluidity, excess, and loss.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 4aarts and entertainment. 4acold war era music. 4aconcert hall. 4acrossover work. 4aevolution of music. 4aexcess. 4aexperimental music. 4afluidity. 4amusic composition. 4amusic criticism. 4amusic theory. 4amusical anthropology. 4amusical theorists. 4amusician. 4amusicians. 4apermission. 4apolitical and cultural influence. 4aremix culture. 4asampling music. 4asound art. 4astring quartets. 4awestern art. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959040423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97805